rComments: Used homophobic language in class and often makes jokes that are uncomfortable and discouraging for students from joining discussions. He makes it harder for you to succeed by not posting assignment instructions on Quercus or anywhere online. He is a poor lecturer because he rarely gets through his material and doesn't take breaks.
His class is the only one I have this semester that doesn't put me straight to sleep!! Very interesting lectures and he is really funny :)
he is the best. his poetry class has made me a better writer and thinker.

Fantastic prof. His lectures were intelligent, witty, and extremely thorough; they also contained humorous anecdotes and occasionally home-made treats. His 3rd year modernist poetry course isn't for the faint of heart (6 short essays, 2 term papers, and a final exam on difficult material) but was an excellent learning experience.
He thinks he's very funny. You might disagree. Also, he hates it when people are not in class on the minute it starts, but he holds everybody at the end of class so now they will be late.

Most difficult exam I have ever wrote for a course, but he is by far the most clear lecturer who is still able to maintain depth in subject matter. I recommend this class to all English majors and specialists, since he will teach you transferable close-reading skills at a higher level than any other second year course that I have experienced.
teacherRatingTags: ['Clear grading criteria', 'Gives good feedback', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: Loved the material, terrific content - you will learn a tremendous amount but the exams are very difficult and the assignments are graded very critically.  Toughest course I have ever taken, don't take as an elective.

One of my favourite profs- tries hard to learn his students' names (so participate so he can learn it better); love his sense of humour (witty and makes fun of himself a lot); explains extremely clearly. difficult course but if you pay attention and do th reading it will be okay
Best prof I've had at UofT ever.

He's great. He makes it crystal clear how to be graded well and give students every resource to succeed. Completely hilarious and witty as well as eccentric. Snappy dresser and very interested in poetry/extremely knowledgeable. But don't take this class if you're looking for an "easy grade".

woodland has a very interesting personality and sense of humour,which made me feel a little better.he's a very tough marker,probably tougher than mot english profs.the material can be hard to follow along.his tests/exams are huge throw-offs and barely cover texts from class

Great prof. Always willing to help students. Witty. I thought he did a far better job at explaining things compared to our textbook. He obviously has a passion and enthusiasm for poetry and I admire that. One of my faves this year. For me, poetry is quite challenging, but I don't regret taking this course. I learned a lot.

Easily one of the best professors i've had. He seems to have memorized every poem ever and can recall them on demand. I'm a lover of modern poetry and he made me love it even more. He made long lectures more amusing with his wit and was very easy to speak to if anything needed to be clarified.

Terribly unhelpful. Difficult to approach if you're not his favourite. Makes a lot of jokes about his mother, followed by nervous laughter in the class. I enjoy modern poetry when outside of his classroom.

this class is not for the faint-hearted essay writer. Prof. Woodland is a meticulous grader, and there is no room for wishy-washiness. He is VERY funny, and quite personable though. He even made us cake. I still dislike modern poetry, but I had fun with the prof. Some of the stdents were annoying though.

I am getting a A in his course but I find him difficult to understand sometimes. He needs to be more clear. But he is a very energic and funny proff. But he is hard. ENG348 is tough, and only true poetry lovers should take it.

ENG348 is, as Woodland states clearly, considered the departments most difficult undergraduate class. The material is difficult. Contrary to the complaints of disgruntled students, however, Woodland is amazingly clever and insightful. If you are a good student, you will love his class. So no fear. Modernist poetry is tough but he helps us enjoy it.

This class is the definition of pretentious. I love modern poetry, but I feel that you have to fight in order for him to respect your ideas. His lectures aren't bad to listen to, and he really does try to be funny... but sometimes you just don't know how to take it. Given the chance, I don't think I'd take it again.

witty, extremely brilliant, thought provoking class. I thorougly enjoyed his analysis of the poetry pieces .He is an insightful instructor and I am very glad i had the pleasure of his teaching.He is worth every penny of my tuition plus his humour is one of a kind.if he is that funny sober, i would honestly like to see what he is like inebriated.

Stevens seminar.  Prof. Woodland is an exceptionally lucid, intelligent, and, despite what some others have said, open-minded professor.  Be prepared to support your readings, however.  His egotism is purely self-reflexive; what others call his "attitude" is actually a manifestation of his wonderful sense of humour and endearing wit.
What a fantastic professor: clear, insightful, fair grader, and funny. It was really great being in his class. 10/10

He's absolutely phenomnal! His lectures are structured, thoughtful, stimulating, and his exams are fair. If you do the work and you show up it helps a lot. If you are not good at coming to class don't take it because then you will find the marking hard, and the work challenging when you do. He is one of the best prof's I ever had!

Hardest course I ever took since I poetically challenged, but I massively improved after taking this class.  He's one of the smartest professors I have ever had and he's hilarious.  His sense of humour made the 3 hour lecture more bearable.
He sure does love himself even if I didn't...

Outstanding! Neither of these were bird courses, but they were very rewarding. Those who complain about his ego obviously don't have a sense of humour.  He's genuinely a nice person and is open to new interpretations of texts.

I think people who don't like him are just bitter because they get bad marks. He is an excellent, v. intelligent prof, great material, good lectures. His "conceitedness" is totally played-up to be funny. He does try hard for laughs but he is funny, so it doesn't matter. He is a fair marker, smart, & kind to stupid people. Highly recommend.

he's very knowledgeable and provides intresting interpretations of the poetry. but his attitute STINKS. it must be hard for him to see past his massive ego. this guy is arrogant, self-obsessed and condescending. be prepared to listen to him talk about himself *every* class. not a good class for rebellious types who disagree with his opinions.

I love him!  He's really funny, open, and the material (so far) is really good.  He makes a weird face, though, when he's listening to students like he's taking a really hard crap, and he enunciates pretty much every syllable and repeats everything three times, which makes him super easy to take notes from.  A-

Wow, looking at the comments from the other class is kinda shocking.  People in my class LOVE him, he really does love poetry with a great knowledge in the field and I think he's a great teacher.  Work is not easy at all but compared to some other courses, I'd take this over it for sure.  He's 40sth but looks like 20-30 to me, scary.  Free candy.
Never again.
A highly eloquent speaker:  rational, insightful, accurate.  Undoubtedly among the best poetry professors at the university.

An extremely intelligent man, no doubt, who gave fascinating lectures, but I found him to be narrowminded, pretentious, and arrogant. His interpretation of the poems were THE correct interpretation. Very hard marker.

He was a funny guy and sort of an interesting lecturer, but everything was about sex.  It got to be a bit much.  Also, he's really narrow minded and not very helpful if you're trying to do something different, or say something he doesn't agree with.
